sql:
SELECT wc.class_name, p.predicted_quality
FROM wine_classes wc
JOIN predictions p ON wc.class_id = p.wine_id;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT property_name) AS unique_property_count
FROM chemical_properties cp
JOIN predictions p ON cp.wine_id = p.wine_id;

SELECT researcher_name, email
FROM researchers
WHERE researcher_id NOT IN (
    SELECT researcher_id
    FROM access_logs
);

external_knowledge:
- This question assumes that the chemical property values are numeric and can be averaged.; 
- The prediction count for each class includes all predictions made, regardless of their accuracy or type.; 
- The query does not filter or order the results based on any specific criteria, providing a comprehensive overview of all wine classes.

sql:
SELECT quality_metrics.metric_value
FROM quality_metrics
JOIN chemical_properties ON quality_metrics.wine_id = chemical_properties.wine_id;

SELECT class_name, description 
FROM wine_classes 
ORDER BY class_name ASC;
